    "dailyBrief": {
        "brent": 76,
        "brentDeltaPct": -0.22,
        "bullets": [
            "Washington is demanding Iran issue a public statement guaranteeing the Strait of Hormuz is open and that ships will not be attacked, per Marine Insight.",
            "The Hormuz Index Crisis Pressure reads 86 (extreme), while the 30-day Escalation Forecast holds at 61 (high), with top pressure still driven by indexed events.",
            "PortWatch recorded 34 transits on 2026-07-05, against a pre-crisis baseline of 88 per day; 517 vessels remain anchored or stopped in the region."
        ],
        "date": "2026-07-11",
        "generatedAt": "2026-07-11T11:52:30.775Z",
        "source": "claude",
        "summary": "The Strait of Hormuz sits at the center of an intensifying diplomatic standoff, with Washington pressing Tehran for a public commitment to safe passage even as Iran's top diplomat, Araghchi, met counterparts in Oman for talks the ceasefire's stability depended on, per The National News and the New York Times. The U.S. has warned of a response to continued attacks and, per Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty, says Iran acknowledged a 'mistake' in recent strait incidents ahead of those talks. Operationally, congestion remains severe: 517 vessels are anchored or stopped, and scraper-derived 24-hour arrivals at Gulf ports totaled 395, a figure that reflects independent methodology and should not be compared directly to PortWatch data. PortWatch's most recent published day, 2026-07-05, recorded 34 transits, a fraction of the pre-crisis baseline of 88 per day. The divergence between the Hormuz Index's current-state reading of 86 (extreme) and its 30-day forecast composite of 61 (high) is significant: present conditions remain in crisis territory while the forward view, driven chiefly by Polymarket closure odds, prices in some probability of de-escalation. Brent is unchanged at $76.00 since the prior brief on 2026-07-10, suggesting oil markets are treating the Oman talks as a credible, if unresolved, off-ramp. A proposed Syria-Iraq-U.S. Mediterranean pipeline deal, reported exclusively by Middle East Eye, underscores how seriously bypass options are now being evaluated.",
        "transitsToday": 34
    },
